It turns out this is merely another way the new course enrollment system conspires to increase the stress of undergraduate students and department staff.

Here is what happens (edited for clarity) according to central campus project staff -- thanks Lydia for researching this:

As soon as any student adds to the wait list of a particular course (say a non-major for a CS upper div --, all students who try to enroll in that class (including student who should be able to enroll) are prompted to add to the wait list. Then, when the wait list process runs, students who do qualify to enroll in the class are enrolled. The class will then open back up and students who meet the reserve cap will be able to enroll until another student adds to the wait list.

As of yesterday morning, the wait list process had not yet run for Spring 2017 but it seems like it must have done so yesterday evening.  When the process runs, students who meet the reserve cap will be enrolled (provided they don't have any time conflicts or haven't reached the unit max for Phase 1).

See above.

No.  The new student enrollment system does not currently have any significant way for us to distinguish between juniors and seniors for enrollment purposes.

Unfortunately not everyone signing up for the class would "gladly take that risk" or even read on here to see that it is a risk. Cancelling a course causes more disruption for student schedules/financial aid/visas than delaying the opening of a course.

"The new student enrollment system does not currently have any significant way for us to distinguish between juniors and seniors for enrollment purposes."

Couldn't you use CalCentral's "Terms in Attendance"?

That is something we decided not to do for upper div classes when we've always counted junior and senior standing by unit.  If that functionality never appears in the new system, we may fall back on what you suggest. It won't be for this semester.

COMPSCI 194-30 (Practical Networking) is now scheduled for TT 12:30-2P in 420 Soda.

Students who wish to take this class should add themselves to the waitlist and also fill out the form here: https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/PHT37GH 

Waitlist position will not impact your ability to be accepted into the class. Using phase 2 units to waitlist will be fine.  The instructors are only expecting to accept 20 students so definitely have a backup plan in case you aren't selected.

CS10 is now open for enrollment -- although with 4 labs and 4 discussions instead of the initially projected 8 each. Students should be able to sign up when their phase 2 appointment has occurred.  Note: Given the constricted size of the class, the instructor has decided that at least for the time being enrollment is being prioritized for first and fourth year students.

TA hiring was a good guess but it's not actually the case here. More students are not being moved into the course for one of two reasons:

1) They are not declared cs/eecs majors and only declared cs/eecs majors can enroll into upper div cs classes until the beginning of the adjustment period (this means that students who are in the process of declaring may be moved in soon -- shortly before adjustment period begins).

2) Declared cs/eecs majors are waitlisted for full discussion sections.
